  <p>The Rabbit (<span class="chinese-char">兔</span>, tù) holds the fourth position in the Chinese zodiac cycle. In classical Chinese cosmology, the Rabbit is associated with the Earthly Branch <strong>Mao (卯)</strong>, representing the gentle hours of early morning from 5am to 7am — when the world awakens softly, dew glistens on grass, and the first birdsong breaks the silence. This placement reflects the Rabbit's essential nature: gentle, perceptive, and attuned to beauty.</p>
  <p>The Rabbit has deep roots in Chinese mythology, most notably as the <strong>Jade Rabbit (玉兔)</strong> who lives on the moon, eternally pounding the elixir of immortality with a jade mortar and pestle. This lunar connection is documented in texts as early as the <em>Chu Ci</em> (楚辭, 3rd century BCE) and reinforced the Rabbit's association with longevity, purity, and the feminine Yin principle.</p>
